(
  'Thomas Townsend Brown / Electrogravitics Research (1920s-1970s)',
  'thomas-townsend-brown-electrogravitics',
  'Thomas Townsend Brown demonstrated electrogravitics — thrust generation through high-voltage electrostatic fields — beginning in the 1920s. After attracting serious U.S. military interest in the 1950s, his research was classified and he was effectively removed from the public record. Declassified documents confirm the U.S. Air Force conducted Project Winterhaven, evaluating electrogravitics as a propulsion technology.',
  'Thomas Townsend Brown (1905-1985) began demonstrating what he called the Biefeld-Brown effect in the 1920s — the apparent movement of a capacitor toward its positive pole when charged to high voltage, which Brown attributed to a connection between electromagnetism and gravity. By the 1950s, his work had attracted interest from the U.S. Navy, and a declassified document — the Electrogravitics Systems report prepared by the Aviation Studies International Ltd. company in 1956 — confirmed that the major aerospace companies including Convair, Glenn Martin, Bell Aircraft, and others were seriously researching electrogravitics as a potential aircraft and spacecraft propulsion system. By the late 1950s, all public discussion of electrogravitics in aerospace journals ceased abruptly. Brown continued his research under private funding and in classified settings. His later career was largely kept from the public record. Researchers and declassified documents suggest the U.S. government classified the field after determining its potential as a propulsion breakthrough.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biefeld%E2%80%93Brown_effect',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1956-01-01',
  '{"category": "Suppressed propulsion technology / military classification", "importance": "SILVER", "tags": ["Thomas Townsend Brown", "electrogravitics", "Biefeld-Brown effect", "classified research", "propulsion", "anti-gravity"]}'
),

(
  'Tesla / Wardenclyffe Tower / JP Morgan Suppression (1901-1917)',
  'tesla-wardenclyffe-jp-morgan-suppression',
  'Nikola Tesla''s Wardenclyffe Tower project — designed to provide free wireless electrical transmission globally — was defunded by J.P. Morgan in 1906 after Morgan reportedly asked who would pay for it. Tesla''s patents were acquired by Westinghouse; after his death in 1943, the FBI seized his papers. The U.S. government did not return Tesla''s documents for decades; some remain classified.',
  'Nikola Tesla began construction of the Wardenclyffe Tower on Long Island, New York in 1901, funded initially by J.P. Morgan. Tesla''s stated design was for a global wireless communication and electrical power transmission system — one that would make electrical power freely available to anyone with a receiving device. According to Tesla''s account, when he revealed to Morgan that the system would transmit free power globally, Morgan withdrew funding in 1906, reportedly asking how anyone would put a meter on it. The tower was never completed and was demolished in 1917. Tesla died in 1943, largely destitute, in a New York hotel room. Within hours of his death, the U.S. Office of Alien Property seized his papers, documents, and research notes — despite Tesla being an American citizen — and held them classified for years. Tesla''s alternating current (AC) electrical system became the global standard; his work on wireless power transmission, resonance, and free energy remained largely suppressed in mainstream academic literature for decades after his death.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wardenclyffe_Tower',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1906-01-01',
  '{"category": "Free energy suppression / corporate financial control", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["Tesla", "Wardenclyffe", "JP Morgan", "free energy", "wireless power", "classified documents"]}'
),

(
  'Eugene Mallove / Cold Fusion Murder (1989-2004)',
  'eugene-mallove-cold-fusion-murder',
  'Eugene Mallove, editor of Infinite Energy magazine and the most prominent U.S. advocate for cold fusion and low-energy nuclear reactions (LENR), was murdered in May 2004. A MIT scientist who had reviewed the original Pons-Fleischmann cold fusion experiment, Mallove published evidence he believed MIT researchers had falsified their data to discredit the discovery. His murder was never definitively solved.',
  'On March 23, 1989, University of Utah chemists Stanley Pons and Martin Fleischmann announced they had achieved nuclear fusion at room temperature — cold fusion — in a tabletop experiment. Within months, much of the scientific establishment had declared the results fraudulent. Eugene Mallove, then a science writer at MIT, later published evidence suggesting that MIT researchers had falsified their analysis of their cold fusion replication attempt — specifically that raw data showing positive results had been altered in published reports to show a flat result. Mallove founded Infinite Energy magazine and spent 15 years documenting low-energy nuclear reaction (LENR) research worldwide, arguing that the scientific establishment and energy industry had conspired to suppress the technology. On May 14, 2004, Mallove was found beaten to death at his family''s rental property in Norwich, Connecticut. A man was eventually convicted of the murder under circumstances that many observers characterized as robbery — though Mallove''s colleagues have raised questions about the investigation.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eugene_Mallove',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2004-05-14',
  '{"category": "Cold fusion suppression / scientist death", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["Eugene Mallove", "cold fusion", "LENR", "MIT data falsification", "murder", "energy suppression"]}'
),

(
  'Viktor Schauberger / Implosion Technology (1930s-1958)',
  'viktor-schauberger-implosion-technology',
  'Austrian forest warden and inventor Viktor Schauberger developed implosion-based water and energy technologies based on his observations of natural vortex motion in streams. His work attracted Nazi interest during WWII; after the war, American military personnel confiscated his research. In 1958, Schauberger traveled to the U.S. where his remaining documents and prototypes were taken from him. He died five days after returning home.',
  'Viktor Schauberger (1885-1958) was an Austrian forester and inventor who developed theories about natural water movement and implosion — the opposite of explosion as an energy principle. Schauberger observed that trout in mountain streams could hold position against strong currents with minimal effort using spiral movement, and theorized that nature uses implosive, centripetal forces rather than the explosive, centrifugal forces used in conventional engines. He developed working prototypes of implosion-based devices, water purification systems, and what he called a Repulsine — an implosion turbine. During WWII, Schauberger was allegedly forced to work for the SS on propulsion-related research. After the war, according to accounts by his family and colleagues, American military personnel confiscated his documents and prototypes. In 1958, Schauberger was brought to the United States by Texas investors; after signing over the rights to his work under disputed circumstances, he returned to Austria. He died five days later, allegedly saying "they took everything from me." His grandson Jorg Schauberger has continued efforts to document and revive his work.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Viktor_Schauberger',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1958-09-25',
  '{"category": "Suppressed technology / inventor persecution", "importance": "SILVER", "tags": ["Viktor Schauberger", "implosion", "vortex energy", "confiscated research", "Nazi", "suppressed technology"]}'
),

(
  'John Bedini / Free Energy Devices (1980s-Present)',
  'john-bedini-free-energy-devices',
  'John Bedini, an American inventor and audio engineer, developed numerous devices he claimed could charge batteries with more energy output than input — so-called free energy or over-unity devices. His patents are documented in the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office. Bedini claimed to have been approached by government agents warning him to stop development; he died in 2016 before independently verified replication was established.',
  'John Bedini (1944-2016) was an American inventor, electronics engineer, and audio equipment designer who claimed to have developed battery charging devices exhibiting over-unity energy characteristics — devices that could charge batteries while outputting more energy than was input. Bedini held multiple U.S. patents on his designs and published technical papers describing his methods. His most well-known device, the Bedini SG (School Girl Motor), was designed to be easily replicable as a demonstration. Bedini claimed throughout his life that representatives of government agencies and energy industry interests had visited him and warned him to stop publicizing his work. His devices attracted significant interest in the alternative energy community; independent replication attempts have produced mixed results. Bedini died in November 2016; his work remains controversial within the scientific community, though supporters argue that mainstream science has not conducted proper peer-reviewed testing of his designs.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Bedini',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1984-01-01',
  '{"category": "Over-unity device / free energy suppression", "importance": "PRELIMINARY", "tags": ["John Bedini", "free energy", "over-unity", "battery charging", "suppressed technology", "patents"]}'
),

(
  'Invention Secrecy Act: Classified Patent Suppression (1951-Present)',
  'invention-secrecy-act-patent-suppression',
  'The Invention Secrecy Act of 1951 allows the U.S. government to classify private inventors'' patent applications and impose secrecy orders preventing public disclosure. As of 2023, approximately 5,900 patent applications are under active secrecy orders. The law has been used to suppress energy-related inventions, with inventors receiving no compensation while their work is held classified for years or decades.',
  'The Invention Secrecy Act of 1951 (35 U.S.C. § 181-188) authorizes federal agencies to review patent applications and impose secrecy orders on any invention they deem to be "detrimental to national security." Once a secrecy order is imposed, the inventor cannot publicly disclose or commercialize their invention; the order can be renewed indefinitely. Inventors receive no compensation for the period their invention is suppressed. As of fiscal year 2023, approximately 5,900 patent applications were under active secrecy orders — the highest figure in decades. The categories of patents subject to secrecy orders include advanced energy systems, propulsion technologies, and electromagnetic devices. The Fiscal Year 2021 report from the U.S. Patent and Trademark Office documented that 5,784 active secrecy orders were in effect, with new orders issued and rescinded each year. Critics argue the law has been used not only to protect legitimate national security interests but to prevent commercialization of technologies that would threaten existing energy industry profits.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Invention_Secrecy_Act',
  'verified',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1951-01-01',
  '{"category": "Government patent suppression / classified technology", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["Invention Secrecy Act", "patent suppression", "classified patents", "energy suppression", "USPTO", "national security"]}'
),

(
  'Enron California Energy Crisis (2000-2001)',
  'enron-california-energy-crisis',
  'Enron and other energy traders deliberately manipulated California''s electricity market during 2000-2001, creating artificial shortages and price spikes that cost Californians an estimated $30-45 billion. Audiotapes released in 2004 showed Enron traders joking about stealing from California grandmothers. Enron''s Ken Lay had met with Dick Cheney''s energy task force before deregulation policies were finalized.',
  'During 2000-2001, California experienced repeated rolling blackouts and electricity prices that rose by up to 800%. At the time, officials attributed this to natural gas shortages and high demand. In 2004, audiotapes of Enron energy traders were released showing them discussing strategies called Fat Boy, Death Star, Get Shorty, and Ricochet — designed to game California''s deregulated electricity market by creating artificial congestion, withholding power from the grid, and falsifying power schedules. The tapes showed traders joking about "stealing" from California and expressing enthusiasm about elderly Californians paying higher electricity bills during a heat wave. Enron had direct access to Vice President Dick Cheney''s National Energy Policy Development Group before the California deregulation rules were finalized; Cheney refused to release records of those meetings even under court order. California ultimately reached $9 billion in settlements with energy companies. Enron''s total deception of California ratepayers is estimated at $30-45 billion. Enron declared bankruptcy in December 2001 — at the time the largest bankruptcy in U.S. history.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/California_electricity_crisis',
  'verified',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2001-01-01',
  '{"category": "Energy market manipulation / corporate fraud", "importance": "PURE_GOLD", "tags": ["Enron", "California energy crisis", "market manipulation", "Cheney", "deregulation", "energy fraud"]}'
),

(
  'Thorium MSR / Oak Ridge Suppression (1950s-1970s)',
  'thorium-msr-oak-ridge-suppression',
  'In the 1960s, Oak Ridge National Laboratory successfully operated a Molten Salt Reactor (MSR) using thorium fuel — a technology that produces far less waste, cannot melt down, and cannot be used to make nuclear weapons. The project was defunded in 1973, allegedly because the nuclear weapons program required uranium/plutonium reactors. Thorium MSR technology has seen renewed interest as a carbon-free energy solution since the 2010s.',
  'Alvin Weinberg, director of Oak Ridge National Laboratory, led development of the Molten Salt Reactor (MSR) technology using thorium fuel in the 1950s and 1960s. The Oak Ridge Molten Salt Reactor Experiment (MSRE) operated successfully from 1965 to 1969. Advantages of thorium MSR over conventional uranium reactors include: thorium is approximately three to four times more abundant than uranium; a thorium MSR cannot physically melt down (the fuel is already molten); it produces approximately 1% of the waste of a conventional reactor; the waste is dangerous for only 300 years rather than 10,000; and the process cannot produce plutonium or weapons-grade material. In 1973, the Nixon administration defunded the Oak Ridge MSR program. Alvin Weinberg believed the cancellation was driven by the nuclear weapons program''s dependence on uranium/plutonium reactors and the established nuclear industry''s resistance to a competing technology. Weinberg was fired as Oak Ridge director in 1973. Since approximately 2010, thorium MSR technology has attracted renewed international interest, with China, India, Canada, and startups investing in development.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thorium-based_nuclear_power',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1973-01-01',
  '{"category": "Nuclear technology suppression / weapons program capture", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["thorium", "molten salt reactor", "Oak Ridge", "Alvin Weinberg", "nuclear suppression", "MSR", "clean energy"]}'
),

(
  'Iraq War / Oil / Petrodollar System (2003)',
  'iraq-war-oil-petrodollar-system',
  'In November 2000, Saddam Hussein began selling Iraqi oil in euros rather than U.S. dollars, threatening the petrodollar system that underwrites American financial dominance. The U.S. invaded Iraq in March 2003; among the first acts of the coalition administration was requiring all Iraqi oil to be priced in dollars again. The official WMD justification was later proven false.',
  'The petrodollar system — established in 1974 when the Nixon administration negotiated an agreement with Saudi Arabia to price all global oil sales exclusively in U.S. dollars in exchange for U.S. military protection — underpins American financial dominance by creating permanent global demand for dollars. In November 2000, Saddam Hussein announced Iraq would sell its oil in euros, calling dollars the currency of an enemy. This was one of the first significant cracks in the petrodollar system. In March 2003, the United States-led coalition invaded Iraq citing weapons of mass destruction. No WMD were found. Among the first acts of the Coalition Provisional Authority was returning Iraqi oil sales to dollar pricing. Alan Greenspan wrote in his 2007 memoir that it is politically inconvenient to admit that the Iraq War was largely about oil. Multiple senior officials and documents have confirmed that oil access and regional energy dominance were central war planning considerations, regardless of public justifications.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Petrodollar_recycling',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2003-03-20',
  '{"category": "Resource war / petrodollar system", "importance": "PURE_GOLD", "tags": ["Iraq War", "petrodollar", "oil", "WMD false pretense", "Saddam Hussein", "dollar hegemony"]}'
),

(
  'Hydrogen Economy Distraction (1990s-Present)',
  'hydrogen-economy-distraction',
  'The U.S. government and fossil fuel industry have repeatedly promoted hydrogen fuel cells as the future of clean energy — while quietly suppressing or defunding near-term alternatives. Internal documents from the Bush administration showed hydrogen economy promotion was used to justify delaying fuel economy standards and CAFE requirements, effectively using long-term hydrogen promises as a mechanism to protect near-term oil profits.',
  'The concept of a hydrogen economy — an energy infrastructure based on hydrogen fuel cells — has been promoted by U.S. administrations since the 1970s, most prominently by the George W. Bush administration beginning in 2003. Critics argue that the hydrogen economy promotion serves as a mechanism to delay deployment of immediately available clean energy technologies. Internal documents obtained through FOIA requests showed that Bush administration energy policy advisors — many from the oil industry — recommended hydrogen economy promotion specifically as a strategy that would require decades of development before commercial viability, effectively protecting near-term oil industry profits. The Union of Concerned Scientists and multiple energy economists have documented that hydrogen fuel cells for personal vehicles require three to four times more energy input than battery electric vehicles, making them fundamentally less efficient. The fuel economy standards (CAFE) were held flat for decades while hydrogen promises were made. As of the mid-2010s, government investment has shifted substantially toward battery electric vehicles, which proved commercially viable using existing grid infrastructure.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrogen_economy',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2003-01-28',
  '{"category": "Energy delay strategy / corporate distraction", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["hydrogen economy", "fuel cells", "energy policy", "oil industry", "CAFE standards", "Bush administration"]}'
),

(
  'Solar Panel Tariffs / Industry Suppression (2012-Present)',
  'solar-panel-tariffs-industry-suppression',
  'The U.S. solar industry has faced repeated political and legislative suppression orchestrated by fossil fuel and utility lobbying. Beginning in 2012, the U.S. imposed tariffs on Chinese solar panels following lobbying by Suniva, a foreign-owned manufacturer. Utility companies in Nevada, Florida, and Arizona have funded campaigns and legislative efforts to eliminate or cap net metering programs that enable rooftop solar economics.',
  'The rapid decline in solar photovoltaic panel costs — from approximately $76 per watt in 1977 to under $0.30 per watt by 2022 — has made solar energy cost-competitive with or cheaper than fossil fuel generation in most markets. This economic disruption has triggered sustained political opposition from fossil fuel interests and electric utilities. In 2012, the U.S. Department of Commerce imposed tariffs on Chinese solar panels following a petition by Suniva (a company majority-owned by Chinese firm Shengfeng Bright Power Technology), effectively raising costs for the broader U.S. solar installation industry. In Nevada (2015), Arizona, and Florida, utility companies including NV Energy and Florida Power & Light funded ALEC-connected legislative campaigns and regulatory proceedings to eliminate net metering — the billing arrangement that makes rooftop solar economically viable. In Nevada, 2015 legislation so dramatically reduced solar compensation that the rooftop solar industry in the state nearly collapsed, before public backlash forced legislative reversal in 2017. Internal emails revealed in litigation showed utilities coordinating strategy with fossil fuel lobbying groups.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Net_metering',
  'verified',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2012-01-01',
  '{"category": "Renewable energy suppression / utility lobbying", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["solar energy", "net metering", "tariffs", "utility lobbying", "ALEC", "renewable energy suppression", "NV Energy"]}'
),

(
  'GM EV1 / Suppressed Electric Vehicle History (1990-2003)',
  'gm-ev1-suppressed-electric-vehicle-history',
  'In 1996, General Motors introduced the EV1 — a battery-electric vehicle with 70-100 mile range that generated an enthusiastic customer base. In 2003, GM repossessed all EV1 vehicles from lessees and destroyed them, despite customer attempts to purchase them. Internal GM documents and testimony from executives revealed the company had no intention of continuing the EV program, prioritizing profitable SUVs and resisting California''s zero-emission vehicle mandate.',
  'In 1990, the California Air Resources Board passed the Zero Emission Vehicle (ZEV) mandate requiring that 2% of new vehicles sold in California be zero-emission by 1998. General Motors responded by developing the EV1, introduced in 1996 — the first purpose-built modern electric vehicle from a major manufacturer, with a range of 70-100 miles and significant customer demand. By 1999, the ZEV mandate was weakened following industry lobbying and a lawsuit by the Alliance of Automobile Manufacturers. In 2003, GM began repossessing all EV1 vehicles from their lessees — GM had never sold the cars, only leased them. Despite customers offering to purchase their vehicles at any price, GM refused all offers and had the repossessed vehicles crushed at a facility in Arizona. The documentary film Who Killed the Electric Car? (2006) documented testimony from executives and engineers revealing that GM actively avoided consumer success with the EV1 and had lobbied against the California mandate. Internal documents showed GM considered battery EVs a threat to its profitable parts and service business. The ZEV mandate was not reinstated to meaningful levels until the 2020s.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/General_Motors_EV1',
  'verified',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2003-07-01',
  '{"category": "Electric vehicle suppression / auto industry lobbying", "importance": "PURE_GOLD", "tags": ["GM EV1", "electric vehicle", "California ZEV mandate", "auto industry", "suppressed technology", "crushed cars"]}'
),

(
  'Nuclear Fear Campaign / Media Manipulation (1970s-Present)',
  'nuclear-fear-campaign-media-manipulation',
  'Since the 1970s, fossil fuel and coal industries have systematically funded and amplified public fear of nuclear power as a strategy to suppress the only non-carbon baseload energy source that could directly displace coal and natural gas generation. Environmental organizations including the Sierra Club accepted funding from natural gas interests while opposing nuclear power, as documented in internal correspondence.',
  'Nuclear power produces no carbon dioxide during operation and has the lowest deaths-per-terawatt-hour of any energy source — including solar and wind. Despite this record, nuclear power plants have been shut down or blocked in the United States in numbers that significantly increased dependence on natural gas and coal. Research published in peer-reviewed journals, including studies by NASA scientists Hansen and Kharecha, estimates that global nuclear phaseouts have caused approximately 1.8 million excess deaths from fossil fuel pollution that nuclear generation would have displaced. Investigative reporting by the New York Times and other outlets has documented that the Sierra Club accepted approximately $26 million from Chesapeake Energy (a natural gas company) between 2007 and 2010, during which period the Sierra Club ran its Beyond Coal campaign targeting coal while not opposing natural gas — the direct beneficiary of coal and nuclear plant closures. Former Sierra Club executive director Carl Pope acknowledged the funding relationship. Internal Chevron and ExxonMobil documents have shown fossil fuel companies tracking and in some cases funding anti-nuclear activism.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Nuclear_power_debate',
  'corroborated',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1979-01-01',
  '{"category": "Industry-funded fear campaign / nuclear suppression", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["nuclear power", "Sierra Club", "Chesapeake Energy", "natural gas industry", "fear campaign", "media manipulation"]}'
),

(
  'Geothermal Energy Suppression (1970s-Present)',
  'geothermal-energy-suppression',
  'Geothermal energy — tapping the Earth''s internal heat for electricity and direct heating — is available everywhere on Earth at sufficient depth and produces no carbon emissions. Despite being technically mature, geothermal receives approximately 1% of the U.S. renewable energy subsidy budget. Enhanced Geothermal Systems (EGS), which could provide unlimited baseload power globally, have been systematically defunded since initial DOE research in the 1970s.',
  'Geothermal energy refers to heat from the Earth''s interior that can be accessed by drilling, used directly for heating, or converted to electricity using steam turbines. Conventional geothermal is limited to naturally occurring hydrothermal regions. Enhanced Geothermal Systems (EGS) — which inject water into hot dry rock at any location, extract heat, and return the water — could theoretically provide essentially unlimited clean baseload electricity anywhere on Earth. A 2006 MIT study led by Jefferson Tester estimated that accessible EGS resources in the United States alone represent over 13,000 times total U.S. annual energy consumption. Despite this, EGS has received minimal federal funding. Total federal geothermal R&D funding has been approximately $50 million per year — compared to over $5 billion per year for oil and gas subsidies. Google''s $10 million investment in EGS in 2008 represented more than the DOE had spent on EGS research in the previous five years. No coherent policy explanation exists for why baseload, 24/7, zero-emission energy with global availability and centuries of fuel supply has received such minimal investment.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geothermal_power_in_the_United_States',
  'verified',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '2006-01-01',
  '{"category": "Renewable energy suppression / funding bias", "importance": "GOLD", "tags": ["geothermal energy", "EGS", "enhanced geothermal", "renewable suppression", "DOE funding", "baseload energy"]}'
),

(
  'Dennis Lee / Free Energy Prosecution (1980s-2000s)',
  'dennis-lee-free-energy-prosecution',
  'Dennis Lee, an American inventor who claimed to have developed over-unity heat pump technology, was arrested and prosecuted multiple times in multiple states beginning in the late 1980s — primarily on charges related to securities-style solicitations for his demonstrations. Supporters argue the prosecutions were coordinated to prevent his technology from reaching market; critics argue Lee was a fraudster. Lee continued public demonstrations until his death in 2021.',
  'Dennis Lee claimed throughout the 1990s and 2000s to have developed a better heat pump and related energy technologies that he said could produce more energy than they consumed. Lee conducted public demonstrations across the United States, charging admission and soliciting investments in his United Community Services of America enterprise. Beginning in approximately 1987, Lee was arrested and prosecuted in multiple states — including California, Washington, and New Jersey — on consumer protection, securities fraud, and related charges. He served prison time in New Jersey. Lee and his supporters argued that the prosecutions were coordinated by energy industry interests and state authorities to prevent him from commercializing his technology. Critics and prosecutors argued Lee was simply a fraud. The disputes remain unresolved because Lee''s claimed technology was never independently tested under controlled conditions prior to his prosecution. Lee continued his demonstrations and claims until his death in 2021. His case represents a broader pattern in which free energy inventors face prosecution, and the core technology claims are never independently verified or falsified.',
  'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dennis_Lee_(inventor)',
  'preliminary',
  'Energy & Suppressed Technology',
  '1987-01-01',
  '{"category": "Free energy inventor / prosecution controversy", "importance": "PRELIMINARY", "tags": ["Dennis Lee", "free energy", "over-unity", "prosecution", "heat pump", "suppression controversy"]}'
)

